snippet.textDisplay:
This was fascinating and it made me chuckle... talk about high-end water! You could market it and charge more for it than Acqua di Cristallo Tributo a Modigliani.

I wanted to thank you for inspiring me to get into soap making. It's become a truly addictive hobby. It started me down a rabbit hole that I've never emerged from. In that vein, I have a suggestion for a video. I was wondering if you could touch on detergents. I know that you can convert soaps to detergents using H2SO4. I'm curious about the process and properties.

BTW: My wife (from Edmonton, Alberta) who is not very science oriented, loves your videos as they are fun to watch. You do an excellent job of keeping your videos fun.

snippet.textDisplay: hey Nile love your video. Quick tip I should tell you about how to carbonate water with dry ice easily. When I was younger and had some dry ice i put it in a cup of water and walked around joking I was drinking it. I used this method to make some bubbly water every time I got dry ice. I work with valves fittings regulators gauges ect. every day. That overpriced hose you got looks a helluva lot like explosion proof tubing. I dont know what you paid for it obviously but im guessing it was probably the actual price of it, that stuffs not cheap depending on what spec it is. Any stainless pressure setup is going to get expensive very quickly. Not meaning to be a keyboard warrior or anything im just offering a little info so maybe your wallet can relax a little. I absolutely love your channel man you have some of the best content on here!
P.S. i appreciate that your not afraid of the unkown. To my eyes there were one or two things that i would have done differently with the CO2 rig but thats just me being technical, other than that you did a fantastic job with it especially with this being your first(?) apparatus!
